      • add

        void add(int i,
         T t)
        Inserts the specified element t at the specified position in this set. Shifts the element currently at that position (if any) and any subsequent elements to the right (adds one to their indices). All of this only happens if this set does not contain an element other corresponding to other.equals(t).

        null elements are not supported so a NullPointerException must be thrown if the specified element is null.

        Specified by:
        add in interface java.util.List<T>
        Parameters:
        t - the element to be inserted into the set
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if the specified element is null

      • set

        T set(int i,
      T t)
        Replaces the element at the specified position in this set with the specified element t if the set does not contain an element other corresponding to other.equals(t).

        null elements are not supported so a NullPointerException must be thrown if the specified element is null.

        Specified by:
        set in interface java.util.List<T>
        Parameters:
        i - index of the element to replace
        t - element to be stored at the specified position
        Returns:
        the element that was previously at the specified position or null if this set contained the specified element previously
        Throws:
        java.lang.NullPointerException - if the specified element is null
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the specified position is out of range (i < 0 || i > size())
